   "source": [
    "# 3. Mathematical Operations\n",
    "\n",
    "NumPy makes mathematical operations over large datasets incredibly fast and concise compared to standard Python loops.\n",
    "\n",
    "We will cover:\n",
    "1. **Element-wise Operations**: Basic arithmetic (+, -, *, /) applied to every element.\n",
    "2. **Aggregation Functions**: Summarizing data using `sum`, `mean`, `max`, `min`, and `std`.\n",
    "3. **Matrix Operations**: Mathematical operations commonly used in linear algebra, such as dot products."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3.1 Element-wise Operations (Arithmetic)\n",
    "Arithmetic operations on arrays apply to each element individually. This is highly useful for tasks like **feature scaling** or applying mathematical transformations to an entire dataset at once (e.g., converting temperatures from Celsius to Fahrenheit without a `for loop`)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# 1. Basic Arithmetic\n",
    "arr1 = np.array([10, 20, 30])\n",
    "arr2 = np.array([1, 2, 3])\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Addition (+):\", arr1 + arr2)\n",
    "print(\"Subtraction (-):\", arr1 - arr2)\n",
    "print(\"Multiplication (*):\", arr1 * arr2)\n",
    "print(\"Division (/):\", arr1 / arr2)\n",
    "\n",
    "# 2. Operations with Scalars (Single numbers)\n",
    "# Useful for applying a constant transformation, like adding a bias.\n",
    "print(\"\\nAdd 5 to everything:\", arr1 + 5)\n",
    "print(\"Square everything (**2):\", arr1 ** 2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3.2 Aggregation Functions\n",
    "Aggregation functions summarize data into a single value. These are essential for **statistical analysis**, finding the average of a metric, finding the maximum/minimum bounds, or calculating the standard deviation (spread of data)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "data = np.array([\n",
    "    [10, 20, 30],\n",
    "    [40, 50, 60]\n",
    "])\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Data:\\n\", data)\n",
    "print(\"\\nSum of all elements:\", np.sum(data))\n",
    "print(\"Mean (Average):\", np.mean(data))\n",
    "print(\"Maximum value:\", np.max(data))\n",
    "print(\"Minimum value:\", np.min(data))\n",
    "print(\"Standard Deviation:\", np.std(data))\n",
    "\n",
    "# VERY IMPORTANT: Aggregating along an axis\n",
    "# axis=0 aggregates column by column (e.g., finding the average of each feature/column)\n",
    "# axis=1 aggregates row by row (e.g., finding the total score of each student/row)\n",
    "print(\"\\nSum of each column (axis=0):\", np.sum(data, axis=0))\n",
    "print(\"Sum of each row (axis=1):\", np.sum(data, axis=1))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3.3 Matrix Operations\n",
    "These operations follow the rules of linear algebra. The **Dot Product** is particularly fundamental in **Machine Learning**, especially in Neural Networks for calculating weights and inputs."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "matrix_A = np.array([[1, 2], \n",
    "                     [3, 4]])\n",
    "                     \n",
    "matrix_B = np.array([[5, 6], \n",
    "                     [7, 8]])\n",
    "\n",
    "# 1. Element-wise multiplication (NOT a dot product)\n",
    "print(\"Element-wise multiplication:\\n\", matrix_A * matrix_B)\n",
    "\n",
    "# 2. Dot Product (Matrix Multiplication)\n",
    "# This is heavily used in Deep Learning layers.\n",
    "dot_product = np.dot(matrix_A, matrix_B)\n",
    "# Alternatively: dot_product = matrix_A @ matrix_B\n",
    "print(\"\\nDot Product:\\n\", dot_product)\n",
    "\n",
    "# 3. Transpose\n",
    "# Swaps rows and columns. Useful when dimensions need to align for a dot product.\n",
    "print(\"\\nTranspose of A:\\n\", matrix_A.T)"
   ]
  }
 ]
}